    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-08-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-08-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="435"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d435">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_JCS1">J.C.S.</gloss> Files</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the United States Chiefs of Staff</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d435fn1">Noted by the Combined Chiefs of Staff at their
                        112th Meeting, August 19, 1943. See <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref
                            target="#pg_890">p. 890</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <gloss target="#t_CCS1">C.C.S.</gloss> 315/1</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quebec</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-08-19">19 August
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">“<hi rend="smallcaps">
                        <gloss target="#t_Habbakuk1">Habbakuk</gloss>s</hi>”</p>
                <p>The U.S. Chiefs of Staff have given careful consideration to the proposals
                    submitted by the British Chiefs of Staff in <gloss target="#t_CCS1"
                        >C.C.S.</gloss> 315<note n="2" xml:id="d435fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_989">p. 989</ref>.</note> and
                    have reached the following conclusions: <pb facs="1106" n="992" xml:id="pg_992"/>
                    <list>
                        <label>
                            <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                        <item>By the expenditure of extraordinary effort and consequent stoppage of
                            other essential war projects, the construction of <gloss
                                target="#t_HabbakukII1">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Habbakuk II</hi>
                            </gloss> and an erecting plant therefor is feasible and might be
                            completed as early as the end of 1945.</item>
                        <label>
                            <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                        <item>Construction of <gloss target="#t_HabbakukIII1">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Habbakuk III</hi>
                            </gloss> could possibly be accomplished by the end of 1945. Claims for
                            invulnerability of <gloss target="#t_HabbakukIII1">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Habbakuk III</hi>
                            </gloss> to hull damage may be somewhat justified, but they are
                            outweighed by the operating advantages inherent in conventional carrier
                            types by virtue of speed, maneuverability, and operating
                            refinements.</item>
                        <label>
                            <hi rend="italic">c</hi>.</label>
                        <item>Due to the relatively small value of the <hi rend="smallcaps">
                                <gloss target="#t_Habbakuk1">Habbakuk</gloss>s</hi> in increasing
                            the effectiveness of aircraft operation, and in view of the existing
                            aircraft carrier program, the diversion of manpower and critical
                            materials involved in their construction is not warranted.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
            </div>
